<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Division on `Objective Criteria' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2601004994 Tokyo KYODO in English 2321 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2601004994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Antonio Kamiya] </F>
  [Excerpts] Washington, Jan. 25 KYODO -- Japan and the 
United States Tuesday [25 January] wound up three days of 
high-level talks on the so-called "framework" trade accord but 
apparently made little headway on the critical issue of how to 
measure progress of foreign access to Japanese markets. 
  Japanese officials who took part in the day's meeting said 
the Japanese side has proposed another round of meetings early 
next month in Tokyo. 
  U.S. officials declined to make any comments as they emerged 
from a two-hour session held at the White House conference 
center. 
  U.S. and Japanese officials have scheduled separate 
briefings 
on the framework trade talks at 6 P.M. (8 A.M. Wednesday Japan 
time). 
  The two sides are supposed to draw up a progress report by 
the time Japanese Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa meets with 
President Bill Clinton on February 11 in Washington. 
  But both U.S. and Japanese officials have admitted they are 
still divided on how to interpret the meaning of "objective 
criteria," the most contentious provision incorporated in the 
framework accord which the two countries concluded last July. 
"There is no movement at all from the Japanese side," said 
Marcus Noland, a senior economist at the White House Council of 
Economic Advisers and a member of the U.S. negotiating team. 
  While saying there are problems "in all areas" of trade 
issues identified in the framework agreement, Noland singled out 
Japan's macroeconomic policy and access to the Japanese auto 
market as the "most difficult" confronting U.S. negotiators. 
  Members of the Japanese negotiating team, headed by Deputy 
Foreign Minister Koichiro Matsuura, "are just repeating over and 
over" their positions, Noland said. [passage omitted] 
  Japanese officials say Japan will oppose the use of any 
indicators, arguing that governments in market economies have no 
power to dictate the level of imports for specific industries. 
  Speaking at a news conference Tuesday, Japan's Ambassador to 
the U.S. Takakazu Kuriyama called the U.S. expectations of 
predetermined market shares "unrealistic" in market economies. 
"The United States should understand that putting up a certain 
quantitative goal and trying to achieve it -- isn't something 
that can happen in the real business world," he said. 
  Kuriyama, who is due to fly back to Tokyo this Sunday for 
consultations ahead of the Clinton-Hosokawa summit, urged 
Washington not to "lose sight" of the principal purpose of the 
framework agreement, how to make the Japanese market more open 
to foreign goods and services. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

