<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Increases Offer in Air Base Dispute </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2601143594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1400 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2601143594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 26 KYODO -- The government proposed 
Wednesday raising to 330 million yen the amount of compensation 
to residents who have sued over high noise levels at U.S. Yokota 
Air Base in on the outskirts of Tokyo. 
  The proposal, submitted in writing to the Tokyo high court 
by 
officials of the Defense Facilities Administration Agency, is 50 
million yen more than the government's original proposal. 
  The figure is still some 300 million yen short of the amount 
of compensation suggested by the Tokyo high court in a 
compromise proposal, however. 
  Restrictions on night flights sought by the residents were 
also not a part of the compromise agreement but were 
incorporated into a nonbinding preamble to the proposal. 
  Hundreds of residents living near the Yokota base filed the 
joint action suit against the government demanding compensation 
and a ban on night flights. 
  In March 1989, the Hachioji Branch of the Tokyo District 
Court rejected the residents' demands for a ban on night flights 
and compensation for future disturbances. But it ordered the 
government to pay 330 million yen in compensation for past 
victimization. 
  Both sides then appealed the ruling, but have been in 
negotiations since June following a Supreme Court decision in 
February 1993 rejecting a ban on night flights and compensation 
for future noise disturbances in two earlier noise pollution 
suits. 
  In November, the Tokyo high court sought a compromise by 
proposing an end to the night flights "in principle." 
  Japan and the U.S. have agreed that flights and ground 
activities at the base between 10 P.M. and 6 A.M. should be 
restricted to those that are essential to the U.S. military's 
operations. 

</TEXT>

