<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Aerospace Official Seeks Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2601105394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1018 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2601105394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 26 KYODO -- A top Russian aerospace 
official appealed Wednesday for bilateral cooperation with Japan 
in the aerospace sector. 
  Edward S. Neymark [spelling of name as received], chief of 
the aircraft industry department at the Russian Federation State 
Committee for Defense Industries, said such cooperation would 
benefit both countries. 
  The Russian aerospace industry is faced with an urgent need 
to convert to commercial use due to military spending cuts. 
  Neymark was speaking at a press conference in a Tokyo hotel 
after meeting officials in charge of aircraft manufacturing at 
the Ministry of International Trade and Industry. 
  Neymark said he told MITI officials that Russia is ready to 
cooperate with Japan in any aerospace field ranging from 
electronic parts to joint development of a 600-seat passenger 
airliner. 
  The Russian official is visiting Japan following a 
memorandum 
signed last May between the Japanese and Russian aerospace 
industries to promote bilateral relations and personnel 
exchanges. 

</TEXT>

