<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, Moscow Agree To Open New Air Routes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2601132494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1235 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2601132494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 26 KYODO -- Japan and Russia ended 
three days of aviation talks Wednesday with an agreement to open 
two new routes between the two countries, the Transport Ministry 
said. 
  The accord allows each nation's airlines to operate flights 
between the northern Japanese city of Aomori and the Russian Far 
East city of Khabarovsk and between the central Japanese city of 
Toyama and the Russian Far East city of Vladivostok, ministry 
officials said. 
  Under the agreement, Russia's Aeroflot Airline plans to run 
two weekly flights on both routes as soon as related customs, 
immigration and quarantine facilities are set up at the Japanese 
airports, they said. 
  The first flight between Aomori and Khabarovsk is expected 
as 
early as fiscal 1996 and that between Toyama and Vladivostok is 
expected in fiscal 1994, they said. 
  No Japanese airlines reportedly plan to serve the two routes 
at the moment. 
  The agreement also calls for raising the number of weekly 
flights between Niigata and Vladivostok to three from the 
current two starting in fiscal 1994, the officials said. 
  The two countries also agreed to hold a meeting in Tokyo of 
Russian and Japanese aviation controllers to improve related 
technical skills. 
  During the talks, Russian officials assured Japan that the 
current restriction on trans-Siberian flights will be lifted as 
early as March, the officials said. 
  Because of a lack of necessary aviation control equipment, 
Russia has limited the number of trans-Siberian flights to six 
per hour. 

</TEXT>

