<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chinese-Speaking Men Fire Warning Shot at Ship </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2601013494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0046 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2601013494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Naha, Jan. 26 KYODO -- A warning shot was fired 
Tuesday [25 January] night at a Panamanian-registered ship in 
the East China Sea as 15 Chinese-speaking men with weapons 
boarded and inspected the vessel, the Maritime Safety Agency 
[MSA] said Wednesday. 
  The MSA said the incident took place about 60 kilometers 
northwest of Okinawa Prefecture's Iheya-Jima Island. 
  The 926-ton Nanshin Maru, a freezer cargo vessel, was 
boarded 
by the 15 men from another ship, MSA officials said. 
  One of the men said in Chinese that they were checking the 
ship as part of measures to keep tabs on unlawful trade between 
China and Taiwan, the officials said. 
  The man also told a Japanese crew member and others of the 
Nanshin Maru that he was sorry for the trouble the surprise 
check had caused, they said. 
  Japanese maritime authorities said that between March 1992 
and December 1993 they logged 75 cases of warning shots, 
quarantine inspections and tailings in the East China Sea. 
China has acknowledged that its patrol ships were involved in 
three cases. 
  Japanese officials said Japan will check the latest episode 
with the Chinese Government. 

</TEXT>

