<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Refugee Repatriation Flights Leave for Hanoi </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2101145694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1206 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2101145694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nagasaki, Jan. 21 Kyodo -- Two chartered Vietnam 
Airlines flights carrying 262 Vietnamese refugees departed 
Friday [21 January] from Nagasaki for Hanoi as part of the 
voluntary repatriation plan of the United Nations High 
Commissioner for Refugees [UNHCR]. 
  One of the flights departed Friday morning but did not 
receive permission from the Chinese Government to land in 
Shanghai en route and was forced to return to Nagasaki. 
  The flight's routing was changed to go via Taipei and both 
flights departed around 7 P.M. 
  A total of 263 Vietnamese refugees had been scheduled to be 
repatriated, but one withdrew a request to return to Hanoi prior 
to Friday's departure. 
  The refugees had arrived in Japan by boat between November 
1989 and October 1993 and were being held in the detention 
center and a temporary reception center in Omura, Nagasaki 
Prefecture. 
  The Geneva-based UNHCR returned about 200 Vietnamese from 
Japan to their home country under a voluntary repatriation 
scheme last year. 

</TEXT>

