<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cambodian Official: Hiroshima Must Never Recur </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2201000794 Tokyo KYODO in English 2311 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2201000794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hiroshima, Jan. 22 KYODO -- A senior Cambodian 
Foreign Ministry official, touring Hiroshima's atomic bomb 
memorials, says the tragedies of the past suffered by the city 
and his own nation must not happen again. 
  Sieng Kimhoun [spelling of name as received], director of 
the 
Ministry's Asia Bureau, also visited facilities being readied 
for October's Asian Games and said he hoped to return to Japan 
during the games. 
  "I cannot find the words to adequately express how I feel 
with regard to the pain and misery suffered by Hiroshima," said 
Sieng. 
  "We and the people of Hiroshima have a saying in common that 
this must never happen again," said Sieng, referring to the 1945 
atomic bombing of Hiroshima and the Pol Pot reign of terror in 
Cambodia during which an estimated two million people were 
killed and Sieng himself was forced to labor for four years. 
  Visiting most of the sites for the October 2-16 Asian Games, 
Sieng said he hoped they would contribute to world peace. 
  Cambodia plans to send its first delegation in 16 years to 
Asia's quadrennial multisport event. 

</TEXT>

