<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Groups Resist Growing Rice for Processing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2201083494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0751 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2201083494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 22 KYODO -- Agricultural groups in 25 
of Japan's 47 prefectures have decided not to grow rice to be 
used for processing, a survey by KYODO NEWS SERVICE showed 
Saturday [22 January]. 
  The survey also showed that agricultural cooperatives in 15 
prefectures have refused to cooperate in the government's rice 
production adjustment program. 
  Farmers in these prefectures were strongly upset with the 
government's decision to partially open the rice market to 
imports. 
  The Central Union of Agricultural Cooperatives (Zenchu) 
adopted a resolution last December not to cooperate with the 
government in producing rice for processing. 
  Zenchu officials said the union plans to urge the government 
to review its farming policy, featuring conversion of rice 
acreage for production of other farm produce. 
  Farmers are reluctant to produce rice to be used for 
processing because of low prices as compared with rice for table 
use. 
  Despite their strong reaction to the government's 
agricultural policy, many agricultural cooperatives acknowledged 
the need for production adjustment because of government 
subsidies. 

</TEXT>

