<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Diet Rejects Minister Censure Motion Over Rice </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2601100994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0950 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2601100994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 26 KYODO -- The House of Councillors on 
Wednesday voted down a censure motion against Farm Minister 
Eijiro Hata over the government's decision last December to open 
its rice market to imports. 
  The motion, submitted last December by the main opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), was rejected at an upper house 
plenary session by a vote of 130 against and 106 for. 
  Some members of ruling Social Democratic Party (SDP) [SDPJ] 
were expected to support the motion, but they voted against it 
or were absent from the vote, resulting in the rejection. 
  Several SDP members played a key role in voting down 
government- proposed political reform bills last Friday, 
refusing to obey the party leadership and joining the opposition 
in voting against the bills. 
  A censure motion was last cast in June 1992 against Prime 
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa in connection with the nation's 
cooperation in U.N. peacekeeping operations. That motion was 
also voted down. 
  The LDP cast censure motions against Agriculture, Forestry 
and Fisheries Minister Hata and Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata 
last December after the government accepted a proposal to 
partially open Japan's markets to foreign-made rice. 
  The proposal was made as part of final negotiations in the 
Uruguay Round of global trade talks under the General Agreement 
on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). 
  It calls for Japan to open 4 to 8 percent of its domestic 
rice market as "minimum access" for imports in exchange for a 
six-year moratorium for replacing all import restrictions with 
tariffs. 
  The upper house had delayed deliberation on the motions to 
concentrate on political reform bills. It did not take a vote 
on the motion against the foreign minister. 

</TEXT>

