<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ramos Authorizes Plan To Help Rebel Returnees </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2601084794 Manila MANILA STANDARD in English 24 Jan 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> BK2601084794 </F>
<F P=104>  Manila MANILA STANDARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Fel V. Maragay] </F>
  [Text] President Ramos created yesterday a new body that 
will oversee the implementation of projects for the social and 
economic rehabilitation of rebels who have returned to the folds 
of the law. 
  The Chief Executive issued Executive Order (EO) No. 152 
creating the National Program for Unification and Development 
(NPUD) to replace the National Reconciliation and Development 
Program (NRDP) which had been rendered inoperative due to the 
deletion of its P200 million budget from the 1994 general 
appropriations act. 
  In the same EO, Mr. Ramos formed the three-man National 
Program for Unification and Development Council (NPUDC) to be 
headed by Interior and Local Government Secretary Rafael Alunan 
III. 
  The NPUDC will have Defense Secretary Renato de Villa and 
Presidential Adviser on Peace Process Oscar Santos as vice 
chairman and member. 
  The creation of the NPUDC is seen as a rebuff to the 
Senate's 
withdrawal of funding to the rebel-returnees program that was 
tantamount to the abolition of the NRDP. 
  The Senate chopped off the P200 million rebel-returnee 
program over the vehement objection of Malacanang which warned 
that such action would jeopardize the peace and reconciliation 
program. 
  The alleged rampant irregularities in disbursements of 
rebel- 
returnee fund induced the Upper Chamber into scrapping the said 
funding. 
  The senators gave credence to reports that funds were 
released for fake rebel-returnees and even ghost surrenderees. 
Malacanang, however, said that action was being taken to check 
the alleged anomalies. 
  The [Malacanang] palace said even assuming that these 
anomalies existed, this was not sufficient ground to withhold 
funding for the program. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

