<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Panel Appeals to RAM To Resume Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2501025594 Manila MANILA BULLETIN in English 21 Jan 94 pp 
1, 8 </F>

<F P=103> BK2501025594 </F>
<F P=104>  Manila MANILA BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Aris R. Ilagan] </F>
  [Text] Members of the government panel negotiating peace 
talks with ultra-rightist groups appealed yesterday to the 
leaders of the Rebolusyonaryong Alyansang Makabansa 
[Revolutionary Nationalist Alliance] (RAM) to return to the 
bargaining table for the resumption of the peace negotiations. 
  Professor Alfredo Tadiar, head of the government peace 
panel, 
said the resumption of talks with representatives of the RAM led 
by Brig. Gen. Edgardo Abenina cannot be suspended indefinitely 
because the country's stability is at stake. 
  "We call on RAM leaders to go back to the negotiating table. 
We hope that the substantive part of the talks would start 
soon," he said. 
  Tadiar explained that talks with RAM leaders were suspended 
last 2 December because of differences on procedures. 
  He said the technical working committee with representatives 
of both panels was about to discuss recommendations on 10 
talking points submitted by the RAM, such as electoral reforms 
and good government. 
  Former army lieutenant colonel Gregorio Honasan, also a RAM 
leader, reportedly complained about the government's failure to 
provide the right wing leaders with security, citing the 
numerous armed escorts of Nur Misuari, leader of Moro National 
Liberation Front (MNLF), during his stay in Mindanao in talks 
with government representatives. 
  Tadiar, however, ruled out any discrimination against the 
RAM, adding that it even failed to avail itself of the 30 
permits to carry firearms issued to it by the government for 
personal security. RAM leaders, he added, only got 12 permits to 
carry firearms. 
  The government panel also said that they remain optimistic 
that sincerity on both sides will still prevail despite the 
initial problems now affecting the talks. 

</TEXT>

