<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Communist Exiles Blamed for Delaying Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2601044394 Quezon City Radio Filipinas in English 0230 GMT 
26 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2601044394 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City Radio Filipinas </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Defense Secretary Renato De Villa blamed Filipino 
communist exiles in the Netherlands for delaying peace talks and 
warned that the government is losing patience. Talks to end the 
25- year-old communist rebellion had ground to a halt because 
rebel leader Jose Maria [Joma] Sison insists on unacceptable 
terms for the talks, President Ramos told a visiting European 
Parliament delegation about the government's problems in talking 
to the fragmented communist movement. 
  Joma Sison issued a statement from his exile base in Utrecht 
last weekend calling on Ramos to drop his insistence that any 
accord should not violate the Philippine Constitution. He also 
asked for a second round of preliminary discussions to be held 
in the Netherlands before peace talks open in Vietnam. 
  President Ramos was informed yesterday by European 
parliamentarians that Utrecht-based communist leader Jose Maria 
Sison and his group no longer enjoy substantial support in 
Western Europe. The group told the president that Sison and his 
followers are now considered an isolated group, where before had 
received sympathy and support from some quarters. The visiting 
parliamentarians explained that the change in attitude towards 
Sison is on account of his continued adherence to the Maoist 
ideology, which now belongs to the past and has almost no future. 

</TEXT>

