<H3> <TI>   Clearer Government Purchase Procedures Urged </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2701132994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1319 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2701132994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 27 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa on Thursday [27 January] urged bureaucrats to improve 
the procedures for government procurements, which have been 
criticized by Japan's trade partners for being unclear, 
officials said. Hosokawa made the call at a special government 
committee to discuss trade issues that require a cross-ministry 
approach. 
  The committee is expected to decide on a new action program 
for making the government procurement process more transparent 
and fair at the next meeting on February 3, the officials said. 
The backbone of the measures will be the compiling of a manual 
for the procedures and creation of a database for bidding 
information, they said. 
  Hosokawa will present the measures to U.S. President Bill 
Clinton when they meet on February 11. The latest steps will 
cover all the government's procurements of goods, but not 
services. 
  The subcabinet-level committee, which held its first meeting 
in August 1985, was set up to handle trade issues that require 
cooperation and cordination among ministries and agencies. 

</TEXT>

