<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   NASDA Prepares for 1 Feb H-II Rocket Launch </TI></H3>
<H4>   Satellites Placed in Fairing </H4>
<F P=102> 94P30022B Fukuoka MINAMI NIHON SHIMBUN in Japanese 19 Jan 94 
p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94P30022B </F>
<F P=104>  Fukuoka MINAMI NIHON SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] In the predawn hours of 18 January, two satellites 
were placed in the satellite fairing of the H-II, which is 
scheduled to be launched from the Tanegashima Space Center, 
located in Minami Tanega-cho, Kumage-gun, on 1 February by the 
National Space Development Agency of Japan [NASDA]. Launch 
preparations for Japan's first purely domestically produced 
rocket have been completed, and only some detailed work remains 
to be done. 
  The two satellites to be launched in the H-II will be the 
OREX, the orbital reentry experimental vehicle for the HOPE, 
Japan's version of an unmanned space shuttle now being 
developed; and the VEP mini satellite, a payload to verify the 
H-II's performance. 
  The 12-meter-tall satellite fairing containing these two 
satellites was slowly moved on a trailer from the satellite 
fairing hangar at 0250 on 18 January, taking about two hours to 
travel the two kilometers between the hangar and the Yoshinobu 
launch pad launch-test tower. 
  Then four cables lifted the fairing up about 40 meters, 
where 
it was docked to the rocket, which had already been placed in 
the launch tower. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

