<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Okinawans Protest U.S. Live-Shelling Exercises </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2001121794 Naha OKINAWA TIMES in Japanese 20 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2001121794 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha OKINAWA TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vice Chairman Isamu Yamakawa and other 
representatives of the Okinawa Peace Movement Center visited 
Choko Takayama, head of the governor's office, on 19 January and 
asked him to exert efforts to petition for the discontinuation 
of live-shelling exercises across Prefectural Highway 104, and 
to stop construction on the P3C communications station. Seishu 
Miyazato, Japan Communist Party member of the Prefectural 
Assembly, also asked Takayama to stop the live-shelling 
exercises. 
  Yamakawa and his party protested the prefectural 
government's 
proceeding with construction work for the P3C communications 
station. They criticized the prefectural government for this, 
saying: "We cannot permit the construction of a new military 
base. Sneaky construction work amounts to a betrayal. I hope 
you work harder to realize the governor's peace ideals." 
  Protesting the U.S. Forces' live-shelling exercises, 
Miyazato 
said: "The prefectural assembly has repeatedly asked that such 
exercises be stopped. The discontinuation of the exercises is 
the consensus of the Okinawan people." He asked the prefectural 
government to take measures concerning this problem. Takayama 
replied that he plans to petition for stopping the exercises 
with the U.S. Forces Okinawa, the U.S. Consulate, and the Naha 
Defense Facilities Administration Bureau shortly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

