<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Decides To Review Aid to Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2201165994 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 22 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2201165994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Following the announcement of the new Russian 
cabinet lineup, the Foreign Ministry decided to review a portion 
of Japan's economic aid to Russia. Japan will maintain an 
outline of bilateral support, such as the $1.8 billion in aid 
that Japan promised to Russia in April. However, as for 
emergency and humanitarian aid, including food and medical 
supplies, the Foreign Ministry will carefully select Russian 
Government agencies eligible for such aid and study whether aid 
is needed at all. 
  This was disclosed by a senior Foreign Ministry official on 
the morning of 21 January. As for the plan to review economic 
aid to Russia, the same official pointed out that "we have no 
choice but to scale down the monetary and financial measures of 
the past" because of the resignation of Gaydar, first deputy 
prime minister and economic minister, who had been promoting the 
radical introduction of a market economy, and former Deputy 
Prime Minister Fedorov's refusal to become a cabinet member. He 
also explained that some people are concerned about the 
possibility that the escalating trend in Russia of seeking 
"major-power chauvinism" may create "antipathy against 
`handouts' termed humanitarian aid." 

</TEXT>

