<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MPT Prepares Foreign Language Radio Station </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1601042194 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 11 
Jan 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1601042194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 11 January Evening Edition] </F>
  [Text] On 11 January the Ministry of Post and 
Telecommunications [MPT] began preparations for establishing 
broadcasting stations which will provide programs only in 
foreign languages. MPT's Broadcasting Bureau Chief Masaaki 
Egawa said: "Tokyo is the only major city in the world which has 
no radio station providing foreign language programs." In light 
of this, the MPT will create conditions for approving the 
establishment of new broadcasting stations to live up to the 
name of the international city "Tokyo." If technical issues 
such as allocation of electric waves are solved, it is likely 
the establishment of foreign language FM stations will be 
authorized within the year. 
  In concrete terms, FM stations will be newly established to 
provide programs only in English. Although it is planned that 
such stations will be newly established in three major cities -- 
Tokyo, Osaka, and Nagoya -- it is expected an FM station will be 
established only in Tokyo at first. The MPT will first study 
technical issues as to whether there will be electric waves 
which could be allocated for a new station. Then it will begin 
to work out a basic broadcasting program to improve system 
conditions. 
  What is behind the issue of setting up broadcasting stations 
for foreign language programs is that with the progress of 
internationalization, the number of foreigners who visit or live 
in Japan are increasing every year. Statistics show 980,000 
foreigners stayed in Japan for more than 90 days in 1989. In 
1993 the number increased to 1,370,000. The number of 
foreigners who visited Japan sharply increased to 3.53 million 
people (in 1991) from 2.15 million (in 1987). In light of this, 
those associated with the broadcasting business have expressed 
hope that broadcasting stations intended for foreigners will be 
established. Moreover, some felt that broadcasting in foreign 
languages is necessary in view of emergency cases such as 
disasters. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

